(verb :name "tenth"   :library "list" :tier "core" :kind "pure" :signature "(tenth lst) -> value"
  :summary "The tenth element."
  :provenance "SRFI-1 §Selectors; added 2026-07-18 finalization"
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(tenth (iota 10))" :note "9.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(tenth (list 'a 'b 'c 'd 'e 'f 'g 'h 'i 'j))" :note "'j.")
  )
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The operator needs the tenth field of a fixed-shape record. Candidates: tenth, list-ref lst 9. For fixed-arity, tenth is the last SRFI-1 named accessor; beyond that use list-ref."
     :program "(define alphabet (list 'a 'b 'c 'd 'e 'f 'g 'h 'i 'j 'k))\n(display (list 'letter-j (tenth alphabet)))\n(newline)"
     :explanation "Line 1 defines an 11-letter list. Lines 2-3 pull the tenth letter (j). The audit tape shows named-position access."
     :meta "Why tenth: SRFI-1 stops here; for position 11+ use list-ref.")
    (:eng "Named accessor for stable position 10; use list-ref for positions ≥ 11."
     :math "tenth returns the element at position 9 (0-indexed)."
     :cs "Named accessor; end of the SRFI-1 named-accessor series."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "A named-position access for the tenth canonical slot; the last of the SRFI-1 named accessors."
     :rungs ((:domain "list" :code "(tenth alphabet)")
             (:domain "decathlon tenth event" :code "(event-10 decathlon)")
             (:domain "π_10 projection" :code "(define (pi10 t) (list-ref t 9))"))
     :explanation "In list, tenth names position 10. In athletics, the tenth event completes a decathlon. π_10 projects the tenth coordinate. All three share: named handle for position 10."
     :meta "The shape transfers where position 10 has meaning; beyond 10 the language expects list-ref."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "tenth returns exactly the tenth element of a list of length ≥ 10."
     :program "(display (tenth (iota 15)))\n(newline)\n(display (equal? (tenth (iota 15)) (list-ref (iota 15) 9)))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ list xs with |xs| ≥ 10. tenth(xs) = xs[9]"
     :meta "The pattern is index-equivalent named access. CS pattern name: named accessor. What would falsify: off-by-one. See book-of-code ch07."
     :eng "Stable named form of index 9; last of the SRFI-1 accessor series."
     :math "tenth = π_10 on 10+ tuples."
     :cs "Named accessor; language stops the named series at ten."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "tenth returns the tenth element (last of the SRFI-1 named accessors)."
     :composition "(define scores (iota 10 100))\n(define last-score (tenth scores))\n(define first-score (first scores))\n(display (list 'delta (- last-score first-score)))\n(newline)"
     :emergent "endpoints delta — pair first and tenth to compute a range delta"
     :meta "The composition pairs first with tenth to derive a delta. What emerges is the delta-of-endpoints family: change between two named boundary positions. See book-of-composition ch08."))
)

(verb :name "list-tail"  :library "list" :tier "core" :kind "pure" :signature "(list-tail lst k) -> list"
  :summary "Drop the first k elements. R7RS §6.4."
  :examples ((:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(list-tail (list 1 2 3 4 5) 2)" :note "(3 4 5)."))
  :provenance "R7RS §6.4; added 2026-07-18 finalization"
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The operator is processing a CSV file where the first row is a header and only the data rows should be handed downstream. Candidates: list-tail lst 1 (drop the header), (cdr lst) (drops one, but the k form generalizes), (filter (lambda (x) …) lst) (wrong shape). For 'drop the first k,' list-tail is honest."
     :program "(define rows (list 'header (list 'a 1) (list 'b 2) (list 'c 3)))\n(define data (list-tail rows 1))\n(display data)\n(newline)"
     :explanation "Line 1 defines a rows list with a header. Line 2 drops the header via list-tail. Lines 3-4 print the data rows. The audit tape shows one drop, k=1 explicit."
     :meta "Why list-tail and not cdr: same for k=1; list-tail generalizes to any k without nesting cdrs.")
    (:eng "Prefer list-tail when the drop count is variable; prefer cdr when k=1 is idiomatic."
     :math "list-tail(xs, k) = drop k elements from the front."
     :cs "Related patterns: [k:] in Python, drop in Haskell, skip in LINQ."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "A prefix drop: skip the first k elements of a sequence and return the remaining suffix."
     :rungs ((:domain "list" :code "(list-tail xs 2)")
             (:domain "skip the intro of a book" :code "(after-preface book)")
             (:domain "shift by k in a stream" :code "(define (drop k xs) (if (or (null? xs) (= k 0)) xs (drop (- k 1) (cdr xs))))"))
     :explanation "In list, list-tail skips k elements. Skipping the preface of a book gives the reader the main content. In streams, shifting by k discards k elements. All three share: forget the first k, keep the rest."
     :meta "The shape transfers wherever a prefix is discarded to focus on the remainder."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "list-tail returns a list of length max(0, |xs|-k) whose contents are xs[k..]; list-tail with k=0 returns xs unchanged."
     :program "(define xs (iota 5))\n(display (list-tail xs 0))\n(newline)\n(display (list-tail xs 2))\n(newline)\n(display (list-tail xs 5))\n(newline)\n(display (list 'len (length (list-tail xs 2)) 'expected (- (length xs) 2)))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ xs k. 0 ≤ k ≤ |xs| ⇒ |list-tail(xs, k)| = |xs| - k; list-tail(xs, 0) = xs"
     :meta "The pattern is prefix-suffix decomposition. CS pattern name: skip. What would falsify: a length mismatch. See book-of-code ch07 on list algebra."
     :eng "The engineering payoff is that list-tail is O(k) and does not copy — it returns a suffix that shares structure with xs."
     :math "list-tail is the composition of cdr k times."
     :cs "Because Scheme lists are singly-linked, list-tail is O(k) time and O(1) space."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "list-tail drops the first k elements."
     :composition "(define pages (list 'cover 'preface 'ch1 'ch2 'ch3 'ch4))\n(define chapters (list-tail pages 2))\n(define (paginate xs per-page) (if (null? xs) (list) (cons (if (< (length xs) per-page) xs (list-tail (reverse (list-tail (reverse xs) (- (length xs) per-page))) 0)) (paginate (if (< (length xs) per-page) (list) (list-tail xs per-page)) per-page))))\n(display chapters)\n(newline)"
     :emergent "content-only slice — a helper that skips a fixed prefix to expose the payload of a structured document"
     :meta "The composition uses list-tail as the prefix-skip step. What emerges is the header/body separation family: split off metadata to isolate content. Same shape as HTTP header/body splitting, as CSV header skipping. See book-of-composition ch10."))
)

(verb :name "list-copy"  :library "list" :tier "core" :kind "pure" :signature "(list-copy lst) -> list"
  :summary "A shallow copy of lst. R7RS §6.4."
  :provenance "R7RS §6.4; added 2026-07-18 finalization"
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(list-copy (list 1 2 3))" :note "(1 2 3) — a fresh copy.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define original (list 1 2 3))\n(define twin (list-copy original))\n(eq? original twin)" :note "#f — same content, different list.")
  )
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The operator has a list to hand off to a callee that may mutate it (via a hypothetical mutation verb), and the operator wants the original preserved. Candidates: list-copy (fresh top-level structure), passing the same reference (unsafe if callee mutates), deep-copy (overkill unless the ELEMENTS are also mutable). For a shallow protective copy, list-copy is the honest verb."
     :program "(define original (list 1 2 3))\n(define twin (list-copy original))\n(display (list 'equal? (equal? original twin) 'eq? (eq? original twin)))\n(newline)"
     :explanation "Line 1 defines the original. Line 2 makes a shallow copy. Lines 3-4 confirm they are equal? but not eq?. The audit tape shows two independent list handles with matching content."
     :meta "Why list-copy and not passing the reference: the reference is aliased; any downstream mutation is observed by all holders.")
    (:eng "Use list-copy at handoff boundaries when the callee is untrusted or the caller wants to preserve the original."
     :math "The result is the same sequence as a value; equality holds under equal?, not under eq?."
     :cs "Related patterns: list(original) in Python, ArrayList copy constructor in Java. Shallow copy shares element identity but not spine."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "A defensive copy: produce an independent handle to the same content so that mutations to one do not affect the other."
     :rungs ((:domain "list" :code "(list-copy xs)")
             (:domain "photocopy the ledger" :code "(photocopy ledger)")
             (:domain "identity on values, distinctness on identities" :code "(define (twin xs) (map (lambda (x) x) xs))"))
     :explanation "In list, list-copy makes a fresh spine. Photocopying a ledger gives you the same values in a physically distinct document. In math, the identity function on a value copies the value into a new container. All three share: same content, different container."
     :meta "The shape transfers wherever a value has both a content aspect and an identity aspect and the client needs the content without the identity."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "list-copy returns a list equal to the original but with a distinct spine: equal? is #t, eq? is #f; the length is preserved."
     :program "(define original (list 1 2 3))\n(define twin (list-copy original))\n(display (list 'equal? (equal? original twin) 'eq? (eq? original twin) 'len (list (length original) (length twin))))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ list xs. list-copy(xs) equal? xs ∧ list-copy(xs) not eq? xs ∧ |list-copy(xs)| = |xs|"
     :meta "The pattern is content-preserving, identity-distinct copy. CS pattern name: shallow copy. What would falsify: eq? equality, or an inequal-equal? result. See book-of-code ch07 on equality and identity."
     :eng "The engineering payoff is safe handoff without downstream mutation risk."
     :math "Distinct identity, equal value."
     :cs "Shallow copy: spine is copied, elements are aliased."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "list-copy makes a fresh spine over the same elements."
     :composition "(define (with-list-arg xs body-fn)\n  (let ((local (list-copy xs)))\n    (body-fn local)))\n(define original (list 'a 'b 'c))\n(display (with-list-arg original (lambda (l) (list 'inside l))))\n(newline)\n(display (list 'original-still original))\n(newline)"
     :emergent "isolation wrapper — a helper that gives the body function its own independent list handle so the original is unaffected by any (hypothetical) local mutation"
     :meta "The composition wraps list-copy around a body call. What emerges is the defensive-copy family: functional-boundary safety. Same shape as immutable-wrapper patterns, as passing-by-value contracts. See book-of-composition ch11."))
)

